            <!-- [The following letter can be found in the folder with the 4 April 1917 letter from Sarah R. McConnell to Paul Ayres Rockwell.  
            It is written by William James Kenneth Rockwell, the son of Paul Ayres Rockwell. It is not dated.
            
            James Rogers McConnell (c)
            
            3.  Letter of April 4, 1917, from Sarah Rogers McConnell to Paul Ayres 
            Rockwell.
            -->
        	
				<div1 type="letter">
					<head>William James Kenneth Rockwell to ?, n.d.</head>
					
				<p>	
            Nothing in literature touches it,
            but from the standpoint of history
            some things might be said.  It is
            my understanding that at Jim’s
            funeral (or service in Paris) three
            women appeared in widow’s weeds,
            each believing she was “engaged” to
            or was the intended of one
            Jim McConnell.  From reading
            Mrs. McConnell’s letter one would suppose
            that Helene Debouchet was the
            rightful claimant.  On the other hand,
            my own Godmother, Mme. Marcelle
            Guerin de Precourt, long time residents [sic]
            of Monte Carlo, and friend of
            Paul A. Rockwell from WW I until 
            her death in 1982, thought she
            was the intended.  The third
            French lady I am trying to identify.
            In the meantime, Dr. Mattox records
            in his NCHR article that
            
            <pb n="[p.2]"/>
            
            two American young ladies showed up
            in “mourning attire” at the memorial
            service for Jim McConnell in
            Carthage, N.C.  Dr. Mattox also notes
            that the citizens of the French village
            where Jim fell are quite familiar
            with the site.
				</p>
					
				<closer>	
            <signed>William James Kenneth Rockwell</signed>
					</closer>
            
            
            <!-- File: McConnell/WJK-Rock -->
            
            </div1>
